ons of human creation from their origins in classical, early Christian, and medieval periods through traditions of representation initiated in the Renaissance. She looks closely at the first scientific reconstructions of the nineteenth century, which dramatized and made comprehensible the Darwinian theory of human descent from apes. She considers, as well, the impact of reconstructions on popular literature in Europe and North America, showing that early visualizations of prehistory retained a firm hold on the imagination-a hold that archaeologists and anthropologists have found difficult to shake.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aHuman evolutionxPictorial worksxHistory. 0aPrehistoric peoplesxPictorial worksxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh1 aGamble, Clive.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook Package Archivez978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501729010423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501729010.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  COR eBook Package Archive  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG